post_text: On 9/10/2020, the Teton County Health Department received notice from Montana Department of Public Health & Human Services (DPHHS) that a Teton County resident has tested positive for novel Coronavirus (COVID-19), bringing the total number of laboratory-confirmed cases to 19. The individual is a female in her 20s. The source of infection is related to close contact with another known COVID-19 case within the county. The individual had been previously identified as a close contact and quarantined, so there are no additional close contacts at this time. There is currently 1 active case in Teton County.

post_text: Could you use some help?
shared_text:
Trinity Lutheran Church
September 1 at 1:13 PM ¬∑

Could you or an organization you work with use some help with a small project? On Sunday, September 20th, Trinity will be participating in something called "God's Work Our Hands" Sunday, a day when Lutherans from all over the country join in service out in the community. Large projects are complex right now due to Covid, but we would love to find some small scale projects that we could do in small or family groups. Do you have an idea for a project for this day? Do you know of an elderly neighbor who could use some help with yard work, a place where litter is piling up or trails need maintenance, an organization that could use some small repair or organizational assistance, or anything similar? Please write a comment below or contact the church office!

post_text: Yay! The city is chip sealing city streets. Please don't park on the ones marked in blue. Thank you to Mike Maples and his crew for all their hard work this summer.
shared_text:
City of Choteau
August 24 at 6:11 PM ¬∑

GOOD AFTERNOON CHOTEAU!

From the City of Choteau Public Works Department the following notice from 6:00 a.m. Tuesday August 25 through 6:00 p.m. Wednesday August 26 .

The City is asking that all streets be cleared of vehicles, campers and other items along these areas indicated with blue lines to allow for the City of Choteau and the Contractor to complete the Chip Sealing process.

This process will take approximately 48 hours from start to finish, and will be completed during the hours of 6:00 a.m. - 6:00 p.m.

It is imperative to the process that these streets be cleared, chip sealed an finished without having to zig-zag around things parked on the streets.

We will begin on the SW side of town and work our way to the north and east. The last road to be finished will be 8th St NW (north of the Outpost Deli).

If you need some place to park a trailer, boat, or other rig during this process, you may park them over by the Weather Beater for the 48 hours.

THANK YOU IN ADVANCE FOR YOUR PATIENCE DURING THIS PROJECT.

Chris Hindoien
#ChoteauStrong
#maskupforchoteau

post_text:
Rocky Mountain Ranger District on Monday responded to a lightning strike fire west of Augusta in the Wood Lake area, according to the Helena-Lewis and Clark National Forest public information officer Duane Buchi.
The Lewis and Clark Hotshots on Monday joined ranger district personnel and a Type I helicopter to maximize suppression efforts on this fire. Currently, the fire is at about three acres and appears to be a lightning-caused fire from the thunderstorms that passed through the area in the early part of the month. These are commonly referred to as ‚Äúholdovers‚Äù in reference to a passing storm causing the initial ignition that then smolders slowly until conditions such as wind, low humidity, and dry fuels allow for active, visible burning.
Buchi said it is important to note that this fire is in the area of the Benchmark Fuels Mitigation Project wherein crews have recently completed actions to reduce the amount of available fuels should a wildfire ever occur in the area.
The fire information number for this fire is (406) 750-8934 or email at duane.buchi@usda.gov.

These are commonly referred to as ‚Äúholdovers‚Äù in reference to a passing storm causing the initial ignition that then smolders slowly until conditions such as wind, low humidity, and dry fuels allow for active, visible burning.

July 7 at 2:02 PM ¬∑

There are COVID-19 testing options available in Teton County.

* If you are a close contact of a confirmed positive COVID-19 case, call the health department and we will issue a testing order for priority testing. 406-466-2562

* If you are experiencing symptoms, please call the health department or a healthcare provider to be evaluated for testing.

For all other individuals, there will be a drive thru mass testing site on 7/8/20 from 10 am - 4 pm on the south-side of the Choteau Pavillion. This testing is for individuals who are NOT close contacts of a confirmed COVID-19 case and who are NOT experiencing any symptoms. shared_text:
City of Choteau
July 8 at 9:49 AM ¬∑

Good morning Choteau - Testing will begin at 10:00 am on the south end of the Pavilion. This is drive-thru testing, you don't have to leave your vehicle.

Please enter on 1st NE and follow the cones into the area south of the Pavilion. There will be 2 lanes of testing and you will leave out of the campground and can go south towards the Weatherbeater, or right towards the Courthouse or left through the ball parks and out.

We are expecting heavy traffic so please have some patience as we navigate through this. Remember, this is the first Wednesday of testing and they will return every Wednesday as long as we are requiring testing.

Thank you all and you can reach me at 590-3031 with questions or the Teton County Health Department 466-2562.

Chris Hindoien

post_text: A Black Lives Matter protest, organized by seasonal Choteau resident Phoebe Michel, drew about 31 protesters, mostly locals, to the Teton County Courthouse lawn in Choteau on Monday. The protest ran from noon to 2 p.m. and was peaceful. It did not draw any counter protesters, and those protesting wore facial masks. Michel, speaking to the group at the start, said the protest was to support efforts to dismantle systemic and institutional racism in America, and was not a protest against the Teton County Sheriff's Office. In this photo, protesters pose with their signs. At far left, Julie Brantley of Choteau, who was not participating in the protest, talks to a protester holding a "Hear Indigenous Voices" sign. Choteau Acantha reporter Courtney Duke Graves and photographer Vonnie Jacobson covered the protest for the local newspaper.
text: A Black Lives Matter protest, organized by seasonal Choteau resident Phoebe Michel, drew about 31 protesters, mostly locals, to the Teton County Courthouse lawn in Choteau on Monday. The protest ran from noon to 2 p.m. and was peaceful. It did not draw any counter protesters, and those protesting wore facial masks. Michel, speaking to the group at the start, said the protest was to support efforts to dismantle systemic and institutional racism in America, and was not a protest against the Teton County Sheriff's Office. In this photo, protesters pose with their signs. At far left, Julie Brantley of Choteau, who was not participating in the protest, talks to a protester holding a "Hear Indigenous Voices" sign. Choteau Acantha reporter Courtney Duke Graves and photographer Vonnie Jacobson covered the protest for the local newspaper.

April 29 at 7:42 PM ¬∑

Do you sew? We could use your help! We're in need of more homemade masks!

Thank you!

post_text:
Significant Spring Storm Expected this Weekend
National Weather Service - Great Falls
Issued: 4 PM Tuesday, April 7, 2020

KEY POINTS
Confidence is increasing that a significant, possibly strong, snow storm will affect much of Montana starting Friday night and continuing through much of the weekend
Much colder temperatures expected for Saturday and Sunday.
Confidence in snowfall accumulations currently low but expected to improve in the coming days.

Forecast Details:
Cold front will bring gusty north winds with much colder temperatures and areas of snow. Flash freeze on area roadways should be expected Friday night. Moderate snow accumulations anticipated. Widespread impacts to roads and highways anticipated through the weekend. Agricultural impacts to newborn livestock should be anticipated.

For the latest forecast updates, visit https://www.weather.gov/tfx/.

post_text: The COVID-19 business closures are devastating bars, restaurants, clothing and gift shops, and more. Collateral damage in the form of lost advertising revenue is hurting Montana's newspapers, the Montana Free Press reports. Jeff and I have pledged to keep all of our staff paid through this awful time. We also pledge to our readers that we'll keep covering our community to the best of our ability. If you love your local newspaper (whether it's the Acantha or some other publication), consider subscribing today, or buy a gift subscription for someone else, or renew early. All of us need to help our locally owned small businesses weather this crisis. Thank you to all of our subscribers and advertisers! We couldn't do it without you.

Death toll from COVID-19 reaches 4 in Montana.

MONTANA ‚Äì Governor Steve Bullock today (March 30) issued the following statement regarding two deaths of Montanans to COVID-19 in the state, making them the 3rd and 4th Montanans known to die from COVID-19.

‚ÄúLosing two more Montanans to COVID-19 is a blow to our statewide community. Today‚Äôs news is a heartbreaking reminder to us all that we must continue to do everything we can to slow the spread of this disease. Montanans in every corner of our state are keeping the family and friends of these Montanans in our hearts.‚Äù

Notification of the deaths was provided by the Toole County Health Department today. Governor Bullock‚Äôs administration is aware of the concerns regarding impacts to the senior community in the county and has been working to deploy additional resources to the health care system.
